{
  "scenes": [
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_81",
      "voiceover": "You shop when you're sad, bored, anxious, or stressed."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_82",
      "voiceover": "Buying something gives a quick mood boost."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_83",
      "voiceover": "But the feeling fades fast."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_84",
      "voiceover": "The thing you bought doesn't solve the problem."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_85",
      "voiceover": "Emotional spending is a coping mechanism."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_86",
      "voiceover": "In America, \"retail therapy\" is real."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_87",
      "voiceover": "Advertisers connect products to emotions."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_88",
      "voiceover": "Feeling lonely? Buy this."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_89",
      "voiceover": "It's everywhere, and it works."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_90",
      "voiceover": "But using money to manage emotions keeps you broke and doesn't fix anything."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_91",
      "voiceover": "You're treating symptoms, not causes."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_92",
      "voiceover": "Over time, emotional spending becomes automatic."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_93",
      "voiceover": "Breaking this means learning other ways to cope."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_94",
      "voiceover": "When you feel the urge to shop, pause."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_95",
      "voiceover": "Ask what you're really feeling."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_96",
      "voiceover": "Bored? Go for a walk."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_97",
      "voiceover": "Stressed? Call a friend."
    },
    {
      "scene_id": "scene_98",
      "voiceover": "The goal is meeting emotional needs without spending money."
    }
  ]
}